# Cursor Rules — junior-backend-quest-v1.1.2

## Stack
- Node.js v20+ / TypeScript / tsx (no compile step)
- No frameworks. No Express. No Next.js.
- ESM modules only (`"type": "module"` in package.json)

## Code Style
- Functional over OOP — plain functions, no classes unless unavoidable
- Explicit types — no `any`, no implicit returns on non-trivial functions
- Early returns over nested if-else
- Descriptive variable names — no single letters except loop indices
- No comments that restate what the code does — only comment WHY if non-obvious

## File Rules
- One responsibility per file
- Each quest is self-contained in its own directory
- Shared utilities go in `src/utils/` — don't repeat yourself across quests
- All output paths relative to project root via `process.cwd()`

## Error Handling
- Always use try/catch on async operations
- Log errors with context: what failed, why, what was attempted
- Retry logic: max 3 attempts with exponential backoff for network ops
- Never silently swallow errors

## Performance
- Parallel over sequential — use `Promise.all` where possible
- Block unnecessary network requests in Puppeteer (images, fonts, CSS)
- Measure and log elapsed time for every quest run
- No `setTimeout` for waiting — use explicit selector/network waits

## Puppeteer
- Always launch with `headless: true` in production
- Always close browser in `finally` block — no dangling processes
- Use `page.setRequestInterception(true)` to block assets
- Prefer `waitForSelector` over `waitForTimeout`

## Logging
- Format: `[QuestN] message`
- Always log: start, key milestones, file saved, elapsed time
- Errors to stderr: `console.error`
- Quest 4 additionally writes to `/logs/quest4.log`

## Dependencies
- Add nothing without a reason
- Prefer Node built-ins (`fs/promises`, `https`, `path`) over npm packages when trivial
- Lock versions in package.json
